            <span id="Chapter_Title_Mod">
            Finding My Ancestors         
            </span>
            <span id="Contributor_Name_Mod">
            teresa roos
            </span>
            <span id="First_Paragraph_Mod">For a few years I was a family history consultant, and I learned much more about doing research and submitting names to the temple. I was able to have the work done for a few of my family members who had passed on and help other people find their ancestors who had passed on and learn how to submit their names to the temple. 
            <br />
            </span>
            <div id="boxmodex3" class="clearfix">
                <div class="ChapterVideoDivMod">
                    <div class="ChapterVideoMod">
                        <iframe src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/124071380" width="500" height="281" frameborder="0" webkitallowfullscreen mozallowfullscreen allowfullscreen></iframe>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <span id="Chapter_Quote_Mod">
                “He was born in Germany, and then all of a sudden he disappeared.”
                </span>
            </div>

            <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod">
                One of the things that I did was to submit all the names that I had to the Family History Center in Salt Lake. By doing that I came in contact with members of my family who were working on their family lines, and I came in contact with a cousin in Germany who was willing to go to the Catholic churches in Germany and verify dates of birth, marriages, and deaths, and share them with me. <br /><br />

                I was able to share information with him about his side of the family who had come to the United States. He especially was looking for my great-grandfather, and he couldn’t find him. He was born in Germany, and then all of a sudden he disappeared. He didn’t know where he went. He finally found out that he had come to the United States with his parents and was living in Freeport, Illinois. He was very happy that I was able to supply him that information.
            </span>

            <span id="See_More_Mod"><a href="#" id="restofstory-show"  onclick="showHide('restofstory');return false;">SEE MORE</a>
            </span>

            <div id="restofstory" class="more">

                <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod1" class="more">

                I got in contact with him through a lady in New Orleans. She was the one who got in contact with Johann Cobus in Germany, and she called me one day and she pronounced the Nehus name “Newhouse”,” and I wasn’t positively sure it was part of my family—I’d never heard it pronounced “Newhouse”—so I finally figured out from the first names that it was part of my family. She gave me the e-mail for Johann, we e-mailed back and forth, and he sent me his whole family line. I was able to add those names to my program and submit those names for temple work. <br /><br />

                Johann is still Catholic and his family is still Catholic, but he was an English teacher in Germany. He understood English and German, so he taught me a few tricks about reading the German records. I was able to read some of the German records and gain the information that he had there.
                </span>
            </div>

