                </span>
            </div>

            <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod">
                That was my main job, but I also took pictures of the missionaries and posted them on the bulletin boards, in the newsletters, and in the president’s office. I helped with other clerical chores in the office that needed to be done.<br /><br />

                We attended zone conferences and that was really good because we got to hear the mission president’s talks to the missionaries. We got to hear the assistants to the president and other missionaries who would speak and bear their testimonies of the gospel. Most of the time they would have a little luncheon afterwards and we were able to attend the luncheons and visit with the missionaries.
            </span>


            <span id="See_More_Mod"><a href="#" id="restofstorya-show"  onclick="showHide('restofstorya');return false;">SEE MORE</a>
            </span>

            <div id="restofstorya" class="more">

                <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod1" class="more">
                The evening before the missionaries would go home, they were able to go to the temple, and we were able to go with them. Some of the times the mission president would have a short meeting with the missionaries, and we learned a lot about the temple from those meetings. Some of the things we knew, but some of the things we didn’t fully understand. That was very helpful to attend those meetings and learn more about the temple.<br /><br />

                We also served in the temple as temple ordinance workers, and through the training we get in the temple before our shifts, we learned a lot about the temple; a lot about how to serve the people who come to the temple to perform ordinances for their ancestors; how to deal with them; and how to make them feel comfortable. We especially enjoyed the temple presidents and the matrons, visiting and talking with them and meeting all those other ordinance workers who we served with.
                </span>
