            <span id="Chapter_Title_Mod">
            A Lifelong Study of the Scriptures
            </span>
            <span id="Contributor_Name_Mod">
            bill roos
            </span>
            <span id="First_Paragraph_Mod">
            I’d read the Book of Mormon and the Pearl of Great Price and The Doctrine and Covenants before, and part of the Bible. Most of the New Testament. But when my dad had his accident—he was in the hospital, then he was in rehab, then he was in a nursing home. We brought him home and I went to stay with him for a month. There was nothing to do. It was wintertime, snowing outside. I’d get out and shovel the snow paths out to the various places and come back in. Dad would sit in his easy chair watching television. He’d fall asleep, so I’d change the channel to something I wanted to watch, and that would wake him up and he’d get after me for changing the channel.  
            <br />
            </span>
            <div id="boxmodex3" class="clearfix">
                <div class="ChapterVideoDivMod">
                    <div class="ChapterVideoMod">
                        <iframe src="https://player.vimeo.com/video/124529457" width="500" height="281" frameborder="0" webkitallowfullscreen mozallowfullscreen allowfullscreen></iframe>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <span id="Chapter_Quote_Mod">
                “So in a month’s time I read the entire set of scriptures.”
                </span>
            </div>

            <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod">
            So what was I to do? I started reading the scriptures. In that month I read the Book of Mormon, the Doctrine and Covenants, then the Pearl of Great Price, then the New Testament, then the Old Testament, and then I read the Book of Mormon again. So in a month’s time I read the entire set of scriptures, plus the Book of Mormon two times.<br /><br />

            Ten years ago, President Hinckley challenged members to read the Book of Mormon by the end of the year. Teresa and I did that, and we’ve read the Book of Mormon every year through since. We’ve just finished a month ago, and now we’re on the Doctrine and Covenants. When we finish the Doctrine and Covenants we’ll go right back to the Book of Mormon again. It’s getting to where even the Isaiah parts of the Book of Mormon are not that difficult to go through. It’s something that I enjoy.
            </span>

            <span id="See_More_Mod"><a href="#" id="restofstory2-show"  onclick="showHide('restofstory2');return false;">SEE MORE</a>
            </span>

            <div id="restofstory2" class="more">

                <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod1" class="more">
                When I’m working in the temple, if I’m someplace where there’s not a whole lot to do, there’s scriptures always available someplace in the temple, and I’ll get the Bible and I’ll go to the Bible Dictionary and read the Bible Dictionary. I encourage anybody to do that. Start right at the front with the A’s and go right through to the Z’s. It makes the scriptures a whole lot more meaningful. You read about the people in the Bible, and you read about all kinds of things in the Bible in the dictionary. To me it clarifies the scriptures. <br /><br />

                In fact, the man we have in our ward right now who is the Gospel Doctrine teacher calls that the sealed portions of the Bible because no members of the Church read it. And you should. It’s great reading. The subject matter changes a lot, but it gives you a greater depth of understanding of what’s in the Old and New Testament.<br />
                </span>
