            <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod">
            I had actually been retired ever since we moved from Virginia because I had done daycare there. I didn’t have a whole lot to do at home, so I did a lot of service in the family history center in Palmdale. <br /><br />

            We came here and I didn’t have anything much to do, so I looked in the newspaper, and there I saw ads for the retired senior volunteer program. So I called them. I saw an ad for the respite program. I called them. 
            </span>
            <span id="See_More_Mod"><a href="#" id="restofstory3-show"  onclick="showHide('restofstory3');return false;">SEE MORE</a>
            </span>
            <div id="restofstory3" class="more">

                <span id="Second_Paragraph_Mod1" class="more">

                I did volunteer work with the Retired Seniors Volunteer Program (R.S.V.P.) in a lot of different locations, like the Sacajawea School, the Chamber of Commerce, the Caldwell Town site, just different places doing odd jobs that needed to be done. <br /><br />

                With respite, I stayed with people who were ill and their caregivers needed a break from their caregiving. They needed to go places and do things like go shopping, go to doctor’s appointments, or whatever they needed to do. I would spend a few hours with these persons. Usually I had a person that I would go to once a week. That was my regular assignment, that I went to this one person once a week until they either got too ill or passed away. Then I would get a new person to visit. I only had two people where I actually went to their house on a regular basis for two or three years. They were very interesting people. I enjoyed doing that.<br /><br />

                By doing community service, I was able to meet a lot of people that I wouldn’t have otherwise met and do things that were interesting. We were also able to usher at the Civic Center, and we met a lot of people there. Through the Civic Center we met a lady who was president of the Historical Society, and then we got connected with Our Memories Indian Creek Museum, and we still volunteer at Our Memories Indian Creek Museum every week, at least once or twice. We have attended a lot of functions with the Historical Society and have enjoyed doing that.
